    InvalidAuthenticityToken error
                            fix ActionController::InvalidAuthenticityToken error, we can integrate the form_authenticity_token helper into the form as a hidden field:
                            <input type="hidden" name="authenticity_token" value="<%= form_authenticity_token %>">
                            form_tag method also automatically generates the necessary authenticity token, so we can remove the now-redundant hidden_field_tag. 
   
    ISSUES WITH USING FORM_TAG and vs FORM_FOR
                            Our form must be manually passed to the route where the form parameters will be submitted
                            You're forced to have duplicate code throughout the form; it's hard to adhere to DRY principles
                              when utilizing the form_tag

                            form_for
                            form_for method accepts the instance of the model as an argument, is able to make a bunch of assumptions for you.
                            form_for yields an object of class FormBuilder #havent learned this yet
                            form_for auto knows route (it follows RESTful conventions) for form data as opposed to having to manually declare it
                            option to dynamically change  submit button text (this comes in very handy when you're using a form partial and the new and edit pages will share the same form

                            When use form_for and form_tag
                            form_for when your form is directly connected to a model. ex profile edit form that connects to the profile database table
                            form_tag when you simply need an HTML form generated. Examples of this would be: a search form field or a contact form

                            form_for is bound directly with the Post model, we need to pass the model name into the Active Record update method in the controller. 
                            change @post.update(title: params[:title], description: params[:description]) to:
                            @post.update(params.require(:post))
                            why do we need to require the post model? params look like this:
                            BEFORE: {"title": "My Title",  "description": "My description"}
                            NOW:    { "post": { "title": "My Title","description": "My description"}}   
                            
     Strong params          setup so that user cant change submital forms, ebcause if they do it will be denied
      to disable            config/application.rb add "config.action_controller.permit_all_parameters = true"
      problem with enable   this means is that Rails needs to be told what parameters are allowed to be submitted through 
                              the form to the database. The default is to let nothing through.
        fix                 permit fields explicitly
        #permit vs #require
                            require:params that gets passed in must contain a key called "post". If it's not included then 
                              it fail (if the key was 'post', could be 'student' etc)
                            #permit method is a bit looser. It means that the params hash may have whatever keys are in it. 
                              So in the create case, it may have the :title and :description keys. If it doesn't have one 
                              of those keys it's no problem, the hash just won't accept any other keys.
        Example:            SEE EXAMPLES BELOW  :: Look for "Strong Params + Create and update" .  
   
   GENERATE
                            rails g <name of generator> <options> --no-test-framework
                              --no-test-framework is a flag that tells the generator not to create any tests for the newly-generated models,
       types
        Migrations          create migration file
                              rails g migration add_published_status_to_posts published_status:string --no-test-framework
                              rails g migration remove_published_status_from_posts published_status:string --no-test-framework
                              rails g migration add_post_status_to_posts post_status:boolean --no-test-framework
                              rails g migration change_post_status_data_type_to_posts post_status:string --no-test-framework
                                will make migration file but wont add anything to change method
                                simply add in the change_column method like this: change_column :posts, :post_status, :string

        Models              create migration and model that will inherit from ActiveRecord::Base
                              rails g model Author name:string genre:string bio:text --no-test-framework

        Controllers
                              Controller generators are great if you are creating static views or non-CRUD related features
                              rails g controller admin dashboard stats financials settings --no-test-framework
                                controller admin_controller.rb
                                routes and views: dashboard stats financials and settings
                              ***This is a generator to be careful with – it can create a number of files that are never used  ***
                              controller generators not the best for creating CRUD based features?
                                this would create wasted code since it would create view templates for create, update, and destroy actions,
                                so they would need to be removed immediately.

        Resources
                              rails g resource Account name:string payment_status:string --no-test-framework
                                controller accounts_controller
                                model :Account
                                views: views/accounts
                              If you are building an API, using a front end MVC framework, or simply want to manually create your views,
                                the resource generator is a great option for creating the code.
                              The resource generator is a smart generator that creates some of the core functionality needed for a
                                full featured resource without much code bloat.
   HELPERS
                              Helpers are methods that are available to your views and encapsulate a common bit of code.
                                ex link_to or a text_field. We can also create out own
    organization              Helpers are generally organized by controller, ex app\helpers\application_helper.rb
                                Not restricted to a single controller, you can also use any of your own helpers in any view.
                        
                              ex: Our last_updated helper is still a Post concern (so we know to look for it in the PostsHelper), 
                                but if an author page or any other page needs to use it they can\
                              
                                  # app/helpers/posts_helper.rb
                                  module PostsHelper
                                    def last_updated(post)
                                      post.updated_at.strftime("Last updated %A, %b %e, at %l:%M %p")
                                    end
                                  end
     application helper         things that aren't the concern of a single controller and are applicable to the entire 
                                  application? For these cases, we have the application_helper
                                  ## application_helper for broader concern
                                  # app/helpers/application_helper.rb
                                  def title(text)
                                    content_for :title, text
                                  end

                                  content_for: send our text to the place in our application layout that is expecting some content for the :title
                                  <!-- app/views/layouts/application.html.erb -->
                                  <head>
                                    <title><%= yield :title %></title>
                                  </head>
                                  see more content_for in http://guides.rubyonrails.org/layouts_and_rendering.html#using-the-content-for-method
   Layouts
    default                 default layout template:        <!-- app/views/layouts/application.html.erb -->

    which layout?
      convention
                            if controller called ProductsController, it'll look for a layout at  layouts/products.html.erb
                            if controller called AdminController, it'll look for a layout at layouts/admin.html.erb
                            can't find a layout specific to controller, it'll use the default layout at 
                              app/views/layouts/application.html.erb.
                            *With the exception of the admin section of a site, most applications use the 
                              default layout for everything, so there's no need to have a layout for each controller. 

      convention override
        for whole controller
                            if controller ShoppingCartController and want to use layout at layouts/products.html.erb
                              (ie: use the products layout for every action:)
                                    class ShoppingCartController < ApplicationController
                                      layout "products"
                                    end
        for single action
                            want to use the products layout only for a particular action : use render
                                  class ShoppingCartController < ApplicationController
                                   def list
                                     render :layout => "static"
                                   end end #other actions use standard defined layout
        no layout for action     want no layout 
                                    class ShoppingCartController < ApplicationController
                                    def list
                                      render :layout => false
                                    end   end 

    example:
      example layout template
                                    <!-- app/views/layouts/application.html.erb -->
                                    <!DOCTYPE html><html><head>  <title>Flatiron Store</title></head>
                                    <body>
                                        <h1>Welcome To The Flatiron Store!</h1>
                                        <%= yield %>    <------------
                                    </body></html>    
   
   
   QuickStart
                            In semi order:
                              rails new blog-flash (creates app and dirs)
                              rake db:create
                              rails s (starts server)
                              rails c (start console) Rails console loads the full Rails environment , irb doesnt
                              helper.pluralize(5, 'laptop') => 5 laptops .  test to see all working
   Routing
    "only" option           selecting which of the seven RESTful routes we care about
                              resources :posts, only: :show   |same as| get 'posts/:id', to: 'posts#show'
                              resources :posts, only: [:index, :show, :new, :create] . #for multiple
    rake routes             See routing order  priority is based upon order of creation: first created -> highest priority.
                              return of rake routes
                              posts   GET  /posts(.:format)       posts#index       #all posts
                              post    GET  /posts/:id(.:format)   posts#show        #single post
                                Column 1 - This column gives the prefix for the route helper methods ex: posts_path
                                Column 2 - This is the HTTP verb.
                                Column 3 - what the path for the route will be and what parameters need to be passed to 
                                  the route. ex post_path(@post) #you pass in instance varialbe and rails knows how get id
                                    should also just be able to pass post_path(3) for id 3
                                    ignore the (.:format) text for now.
                                Column 4 - This column shows the controller and action with a syntax of controller#action                             
    RESTful                 RESTful routes and their rails equivalents
                              Rails   RestMethod	Action	Description
                              index   GET	    /newsletters	Show all newsletters
                              create  POST	  /newsletters	Create a new newsletter
                              new     GET	    /newsletters/new	Render the form for creating a new newsletter
                              edit    GET	    /newsletters/:id/edit	Render the form for editing a newsletter
                              show    GET	    /newsletters/:id	Show a single newsletter
                              update  PATCH	  /newsletters/:id	Update a newsletter
                              destroy DELETE	/newsletters/:id	Delete a newsletter
                                see http://guides.rubyonrails.org/routing.html  
    route helpers             Route helpers are more dynamic since they are methods and not simply strings. 
                                use with view and controller (not model)
      change name             get '/register', to: 'users#new', as: 'register' #disaply /users/new  as /register                                                    
      helper vs hardcode      post_path(post, opt_in: true) is more readable than "posts/<%= post.id %>?opt_in=true"   


    TESTING:                  SEE TESTING SECTION, outside RAILS sections
      
      

    VALIDATIONS
      validations
                              special method calls that go at the top of model class definitions and prevent them from being 
                                saved to the database if their data doesn't look right. AR validate is not DB validate
                                http://guides.rubyonrails.org/active_record_validations.html
      new vs create
                              The only way to trigger validation without touching the database is to call the #valid? method.
                                create forces db validate, new unles valid? is call will not validate

      validation failure      default AR returns false not raise error on invalid
        error messages        look at the model's #errors object. p.errors.messages #=> name: can't be blank
                                check one attribute at a time by passing the name to errors as a key person.errors[:age]
       raise exception        Every database method has a sister method with a ! at the end which will raise an exception  
                                like create!
       
      validators (other than valid?)
        length                validates :name, length: { minimum: 2 } #{ maximum: 500 }#{ in: 6..20 }#{ is: 6 }
        uniqeness             validates :email, uniqueness: true
        custom                validates :not_a_robot, acceptance: true, message: "Humans only!"
        inclusion             validates :category, inclusion: %w(Fiction Non-Fiction) 
        messageback           validates :name, format: { without: /[0-9]/, message: "does not allow numbers" }


      validates_with          for doing many validations in one pass. Look into this

      ex
                                class Person < ActiveRecord::Base
                                  validates :name, presence: true
                                end
                                Person.create(name: "John Doe").valid? # => true
                                Person.create(name: nil).valid? # => false

                                DISPLAY VALIDATION ERROR IN VIEW
                                  <% if @article.errors.any? %>
                                    <div id="error_explanation">
                                      <h2>
                                        <%= pluralize(@article.errors.count, "error") %>
                                        prohibited this article from being saved:
                                      </h2>

                                      <ul>
                                      <% @article.errors.full_messages.each do |msg| %>
                                        <li><%= msg %></li>
                                      <% end %>
                                      </ul>
                                    </div>
                                  <% end %> 
                                  
     ex controller validations
                                  def create
                                  # Create a brand new, unsaved, not-yet-validated Post object from the form.
                                  @post = Post.new(post_params)
                                  # Run the validations WITHOUT attempting to save to the database, returning
                                  # true if the Post is valid, and false if it's not.
                                  if @post.valid?
                                    # If--and only if--the post is valid, do what we usually do.
                                    @post.save
                                    # This returns a status_code of 302, which instructs the browser to
                                    # perform a NEW REQUEST! (AKA: throw @post away and let the show action
                                    # worry about re-reading it from the database)
                                    redirect_to post_path(@post)
                                  else
                                    # If the post is invalid, hold on to @post, because it is now full of
                                    # useful error messages, and re-render the :new page, which knows how
                                    # to display them alongside the user's entries.
                                    render :new
                                  end
                                end
  
                                def update
                                  if   @post.update(post_params)
                                    redirect_to post_path(@post)
                                  else
                                    render :edit
                                  end
                                end#update  
                                  
     ex custom validator      see rails guides for more (can mix/match with otehr validations)
                                  class ClickbaitValidator < ActiveModel::Validator
                                    def validate(record)
                                      unless  record[:title] && record[:title].include?("Won't Believe")
                                        record.errors[:title] << 'Need clickbait plz'
                                      end #unless
                                    end #validate
                                  end #class
                                  class Post < ActiveRecord::Base
                                    include ActiveModel::Validations
                                    validates_with ClickbaitValidator
                                    ...
                                  end
 
    views mapping
      Explicit rendering    Rails lets you dictate which view file you want to have the controller action mapped to.
      Implicit rendering    follows convention automatically look for view file with same name as the controller action.

    Example                 Static
                              adding route ::  in config/routes.rb draw block
                                get 'about', to: 'static#about'  #get url route about this route should be passed through
                                the static controller's about action (ie: method in a controller)
                              adding a new file to the application: app/controllers/static_controller.rb
                                class StaticController < ApplicationController
                                  def about
                                    # render "some_page" #will look for /views/static/some_page.html.erb 
                                    #if render commented out rails will look for /views/static/about.html.erb by convention
                                  end #best practice not use explicit dir name
                                end
                            Dynamic
                              WANT to get to /posts/:id . 222 is passed in app should render data for the post ID of 222
                              ROUTE  # in config/routes.rb draw
                                resources :posts, only: :show . || same as || get 'posts/:id', to: 'posts#show'
                                 see also routing/only above for multiple 
                              CONTROLLER # app/controllers/posts_controller.rb 
                                class PostsController < ApplicationController
                                  def show
                                    @post = Post.find(params[:id])
                                  end
                                end
